{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2feininger_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280605013/1948071601/0024.xml":{"full_text":"Bing Gets a Gorgeous Beauty\nAnd Stage in 'Emperor Waltz\u2019\nBy Jay Carmody\nParamount exports Bing Ciosby as a happy-go-lucky envoy to old\nVienna in \"The Emperor Waltz\" and a happier appointment has not\nbeen since the Wilson administration. The make-believe capita,\nof old Franz Josef is a pushover for the nonchalant troubadour and the\nsurest bet of the summer is that U. S. moviegoers will be the same.\nEven if the customers should be able to resist Crosby\u2019s lackadaisical\ncharm in the picture at the\nWarner, they would have to suc\ncumb to the loveliness of Joan\nFontaine and the delightful Tech\nnicolor vistas of the picture's man\nmade Tyrol.\n\u201cThe Emperor Waltz,\u201d as befits\nits star and its setting, is a super\nspecial piece of entertainment, by\nno means a great picture, but an\naltogether agreeable one. It ought\nto please every one except those\nwho keep on insisting that the\nmovies should be more profound.\nThe elfin minds behind this\npretty project are those of Charles\nBrackett and Billy Wilder, a pair\nof former writers who know how\nto make the best use of Crosby\u2019s\ntalent and Miss Fontaines beauty.\nThev have dreamed up another of\nthose musical fairy tales faintly\nsprinkled with satire which sends\nthe moviegoer away feeling that he\nhas been amused and adequately\nrewarded for his money.\nVienna was its old gaily waltzing\nself at the time of this Crosby in\nvasion. Its Emperor Franz Josef\nwas a tired monarch, no longer\nsoothed by the music of Strausses\nor concerned with political prestige.\nIt is the irreverent Brackett\nWilder theory that his major con\ncern was finding a proper mate for\nhis venerable French poodle, an\nother royal male in danger of dying\nwithout \"a proper heir.\nThis, of all places, is where\nCrosby comes in. His part is that\nof an American \u201ctalking machine\u201d\nsalesman, a wandering minstrel\nsort full of such good will to\nward man\u2014and especially women\u2014(\nthat even palace doors cannot be\nclosed against him. Highest aim\nof his Austrian visit is to get the\nEmperor's endorsement of his auto\nmatic music box, a deal which he\nfigures to bring off most easily\nthrough the beautiful countess\nplaved by Miss Fontaine.\nThese two so unlike humans, the\nbrash salesman and the gorgeous\naristocrat, are brought together by\ntheir dogs. Her French poodle,\nchosen by the Emperor himself tpr\nhis own dog's final mate, has^tne\nmisfortune to fall in lgyy\u2019with\nCrosby\u2019s mutt. v-'\nThis provides Vienna with a ma\njor crisis, but not Crosby. He sug\ngests that the countess should fol\nlow the example of her royal poodle\nand accept the courtship of a happy\ngo-lucky commoner like himself.\nIn the best fashion of fairy-tales,\nthis is what heappens, although not\nwithout a lot of advances by Cros\nby and retreats by the lovely count\ness before things end happily for\nevery one concerned.\n\nInto the brilliant sweep of the\npicture's scene and its gorgeous\ncostuming. Paramount has woven\nmore of comedy than of music. It\ndoes, however, give Bing a chance\nto indulge his vocal specialty with\nthe usual pleasing result. As a mat\nter of fact, song is the major ele\nment in his courtship. He uses it\nfirst to tell Austria how much he\nloves it and, later, to tell Miss Fon\ntaine how much he is smitten.\nThere is not enough of music in\n\u201cThe Emperor Waltz\u201d to make it\nmore than a play with songs. Of\nthese, there is a truly refreshing\ncomedy number, \u201cFriendly Moun\ntains,\" a yodeling refrain in which\necho effects are employed for a\nstretch of the picture's finest humor.\nThe ballad with which the Ameri\ncan minstrel breaks down the coun\ntess' last resistance is a pretty small\nthing called \"Kiss in Your Eyes.\u201d\nFor the huge, ornate finale in the\nEmperor\u2019s palace, the big tune is\nthe one that provides the screenplay\nwith its title.\n\nThe debonair courtship between\nthe traveling salesman and the\nroyal beauty is conducted upon a\ndramatically light-hearted plane\nTHE EMPEROR WALTZ.\" a Para\nmount Picture produced by Charles Brack\nett, directed by Billy Wilder, original\nscreenplay by Brackett and Wilder, musi\ncal score by Victor Young, special lyrics\nby Johnny Burke, dances by Billy Daniels.\nAt the Warner.\nTha Cast.\nVirgil Smith _ Bing Crosby\nJohanna Augusta Joan Fontaine\nBaron Holenia _ Roland Culver\nPrincess Bitotska _ Lucile Watson\nEmperor. Franz Josef _ Richard Haydn\nChamberlain Harold Vermiiyea\nDr. Zwieback Sig Rumfln\nArchduchess Stephanie _ Julie Dean\nChauffeur Bert Prival\nInn Proprietiess Alma Macrorie\nChambermaid _ Roberta Jonay\nwhich makes gentle satire at the ex\npense of both Austrian stuffiness\nand American brashness. Best sin\ngle bit of spoofing in the script is\nthat in which a royal veterinarian,\nwho went to school with Sigmund\nFreud, subjects the countess\u2019 aris\ntocratic poodle to a psychiatric\ntreatment.\nParamount had authorized Brack\nett and Wilder to let themselves go\non the production of \"The Emperor\nWaltz.\u201d The erstwhile writing team,\nturned producer pair, takes full ad\nvantage of this authorization. They\nhave come up with a picture that\nfrequently is even 'prettier than a\npicture, certainly at such times as\nMiss Fontaine is before the camera.\nYou would not want to miss \u201cThe\nEmperor Waltz,\u201d which is one of\nthe summer\u2019s finest, handsomest\nand most sophisticated pieces of\nentertainment. With music, too.\n7 Writers Consumed\nIn Farce at Met\nTHE NOOSE HANG8 HIGH.\" an\nEagle-Lion Picture produced and directed\nby Charles Barton, screenplay by John\nGrant and Howard Harris, adapted from\na screenplay by Charles Grayson and\nArthur T. Hotmail, based on a story by\nDaniel Tradash, Julian Blaustein and\nBernard Fins. At the Metropolitan.\nThe Cast.\nTed Higgins _ Bud Abbott\nHomer Hinchclifle- Lou Costello\nMike Craig _Joseph Calleia\nJ. C. McBride_Leon Errol\nCarol Scott_Cathy Downs\nChuck _Mike Mazurki\njoe _ _Jack Overman\nWalter Stewart_Ben Weldon\nSeven writers are listed as having\ngiven their all to \"The Noose Hangs\nHigh,\u201d new Abbott and Costello\nfarce at the Metropolitan. For all\nthe reviewer knows, they may have\ndriven themselves insane trying to\ninvent something new for the com\nedy team, but the fact is that they\nnever actually accomplished it.\n\"The Noose Hangs High\u201d is mere\nly Abbott and Costello all over\nagain, a couple of clowns living\nin a frenzy of gags which are\npretty much the same as the last\nset.\nEagle-Lion's is the trade-mark\non the latest of the team's incredi\nble adventures. This one has to\ndo with their efforts to recover $50.\n000 which they accidentally took\naway from a murderous bookmaker.\nThe process by which they accom\nplish this is indescribable. It\nshould be enough for the followers\nof Abbott and Costello merely to\nlearn that the two survive at the\nfadeout and will be available, of\ncourse, for another picture when\nthey recover from the injuries they\nmust have sustained making \"The\nNoose Hangs High.\u201d\nThere are other performers in\nthe Metropolitan's farce, such well\nknown ones even as Leon Errol,\nJoseph Calleia, Cathy Downs and\nMike Mazurki. These are gifted\npeople in certain respects, but the\nspectator is seldom conscious of\nthem.J. C.\nEVENING PARKING\n40*\nCAPITAL GARAGE\n1310 N. Y. At*. N.W.\nBatw**n 13th aid 14th\nJames Mason Stars\nOnly Incidentally\nIn \u2018Man of Evil\u2019\nMAN OP EVIL.\u201d a Gainsborough Pic\nture of United Artists release, produced\nby Edward Black, directed by Anthony\nAsquith, screenplay by Doreen Montgom\nery. additional dialogue by Aimee Stuart,\nbased on the novel, Fanny By Gaslight.\u201d\nby Michael Sadlelr. At the Hippodrome.\nThe Cast.\nPanny and Lucy, as children.\nAnn Stephens and Gloria Sydney\nPanny _ _Phyllis Calvert\nLcrd Manderstoke_ James Mason\nChunks _ .Wilfred Lawson\nHarry Somerford _Stewart Granger\nLucy- Jean Kent\nAlicia- -Margaretta Scott\nMrs Hopwood _ _. Nora Swinburne\nKate Somerford_ -Cathleen Nesbitt\nMrs Somerford _Helen Haye\nWilliam Hopwood_John Laurie\nClive Seymore_ Stuart, Lindsell\nMrs Heaviside_Amy Veness\nCarver _Ann Wilton\nDr. Lowenthall_Guy le Feuvre\nBy Harry MacArthur\n\"Man of Evil,\u2019\u2019 which was re\nleased in England about four years\nago as \u201cFanny by Gaslight\u201d (after\nthe novel of the same name), has\nturned up now at the Hippodrome,\npossibly to give James Mason\u2019s\nmany admirers a notion as to what\nhe was up to at that earlier stage\nof his career. The present title\nrefers to the character played by\nMr. Mason. It is an apt enough\ntitle, with reference to the charac\nter, but it really doesn\u2019t have too\nmuch to do with the photoplay it\nself, since the Mason role is a high\nly incidental one.\nAs a matter of fact, the British\nstar, who made his reputation by\nnasty treatment of women, is in\nvolved in a mere half-dozen se\nquences of \u201cMan of Evil.\u201d He kills\nFanny\u2019s foster-father in a street\nbrawl. He sneers at her in the\ncourtroom where he is freed. He\nsneers at her again at the house\nwhere her real father has given her\nrefuge. He sneers at her at Evan\u2019s\nSupper Rooms and is floored for\nhis pains by the man who loves\nFanny. He sneers at her in the\ndressing room of a Paris music\nhall and challenges the man w'ho\nloves her to a duel. He sneers at\nthe man he has challenged and gets\nshot dead in the duel.\nThis may sound like a fair amount\nof action, but it really is only inci\ndental by-play. \"Man of Evil,\u201d\nreally is concerned with the sad\nsaga of Fanny and proves, if noth\ning else, that the British, too, can\nlose themselves in a wave of melo\ndramatics designed to cheer women\nwith tears.\nIt is quite a time Fanny has. She\nis encountered first at the age of 9\nin the London of 1870 and in no\ntime at all it is 1880. She sees her\nfoster-father killed, watches her\nmother die, then is taken in by her\nreal father. He\u2019s a high man in the\ngovernment, though, and can\u2019t ad\nmit a thing. He can\u2019t even give\nhis w'ife, in love with the Mason\ncharacter, a divorce, because, ac\ncording to the evidence of the dia\nlogue, the government might fall\nin the face of such scandal. He\ntosses himself under a train in\nstead.\nIt is only fair to tell you that\nFanny and the man she loves, her\nfather's secretary, come through all\ntheir travail, conquer all obstacles\nfinally, and in the end face a bright\nfuture together. Before they do,\nthough, there is more ado about\nnothing than Shakespeare ever\ndreamed that title could encompass.\nPhyllis Calvert plays the difficult\nFanny role with skill and manages\nto arouse sympathy in w'hat are\npatently lending-library-fiction sit\nuations. She is as matronly-looking\na 19-year-old as you are likely to\nencounter, though, if a man can be\npermitted the James Mason sort\nof rudeness. Stewart Granger, Jean\nKent, Wilfred Lawson and John\nLaurie are good, too. Director An\nthony Asquith has managed to give\nhis film a good deal of the flavor\nof the period, also. But it still re\nmains duller than anything that\nladen with melodrama ought to be.\nAMUSEMENTS\nRed Skelton and Vir- j\nfinia O\u2019Brien \"Mer\nton of the Movies.\u201d\nJoan Blondell and\nGeorce Brent \"Corpse\nCame C.O.P..\u2019*_\nOpen 8; starts 9:00\nAdults. 50c\nChildren Free!\nWhere and When\nCurrent Theater Attractions\nand Time of Showing\nStage.\nNational\u2014\u201cOklahoma!\u201d; 8:20 pm.\nScreen.\nAmbassador \u2018\u2018Emperor Waltz\u201d;\n1:20, 3:25, 5:30, 7:30 and 9:40 pm.\nCapitol\u2014\"Ruthless,\u201d 11 a.m., 1:40,\n4:28 7:10 and 9:55 p.m. Stage\nshows: 1, 3:45. 6:30 and 9:10 p.m.\nColumbia\u2014\"The Street With No\nName\u201d: 11:40 am., 1:40, 3:35, 5:35,\n7:30 and 9:35 pm.\nDupont\u2014\u201cThe Idiot\"; 1:10,